European inflation declined in food
The accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the staggering increase in the price of food products.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording, after 2.6 per cent of October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent, announced the Union Statistics Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only likely to give a 3 percent - Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuers, did not cut the basic interest, on the assumption that the decrease, together with the price increases in raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would result in a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to maintain the inflation rate below, but at least about two per cent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not later have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 per cent, recorded in Germany, beat the record for twelve years, while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation was fired in the euro area as a result of rising food and energy prices.
Quotas at the end of the wheat increased by 88 per cent and soybeans have reached their maximum level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased by 52 per cent this year, reaching the black gold almost $100 barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent, instead of falling to 1.9 per cent for 2009.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 per cent, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
