In many hospitals it saves with disinfectants
This year thousands of infections have been reported in hospitals primarily due to improper use of antibiotics.
Health conditions prevailing in hospitals, bed management and staff overload do not support the control of infections - says the head doctor of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many hospitals, even the disinfectants are saved.
Not long ago, an MRSA infection has been diagnosed in the trauma department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of bacteria resistant to antibiotics was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contamination occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A hit by a serious car accident gave him a lift from the hospital, and the same patient had to return to the hospital soon after, as a result of the infection with MRSA and since then, a major surgical intervention has not been made by the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, nosocomialis Surveillance has been registered in the National System 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents - said Karolina Böröcz, head of department of the National Epidemiology Centre.
This means that in hospitals with full safety, this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents has been recorded, and no information is available.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
A third of humans carry in their nose the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) without causing any disease.
The SA infections (e.g. inflammation of the throat, amigdalitis, skin infections, infections of the wound) respond well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once the antibiotics are applied excessively or improperly, bacteria that normally respond well to antibiotics are turned into very resistant bacteria to antibiotics and are rapidly infected with inadequate hospital conditions.
Severe hospital infections, such as infections of wounds or septicemia, may lead to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with impaired body, elderly or persons with low weight.
In the opinion of the medical director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are everyday in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistant
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff care for them in rubber and mask gloves and there are the appropriate antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are examined beforehand to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but this is not the way to avoid infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA's hospital infections in most cases, but the current national hospital circumstances do not favour prevention of multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the hospitalized patients and isolate immediately the patients who carry the MRSA in their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, the use of microbiological samples is not fashionable.
This fact is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come out in public light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - the head doctor of the department of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union makes strict recommendations for the implementation of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to deal with diseases and diseases.
Antibiotic therapy should be directed, that is, microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent resistance to medications, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological samples are even less frequent in the case of outpatient patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
Save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected with one patient through healthcare.
Therefore, the washing of hands, the use of rubber gloves and masks plays a very important role, but significant hospital deficiencies are also experienced in this regard.
MRSA is infected by drops and direct contact between individuals, but in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, the hospital rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very attached, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals with less favourable economic situation is saved with the disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a greater likelihood of infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate prevention measures are carried out, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the infection of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
The treatment of infection with MRSA is a huge cost to the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is fought against in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The programme appears to be successful, according to the data provided, infections with MRSA show a downward trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
