According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, meetings at the expert level will be completed on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official opening of the ministerial negotiations on the post-2012 international climate regime.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Balí Roadmap, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
There are lively discussions on the particular situation between developing countries and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate precise figures at the moment, although it tends to agree that, compared to the 1990 situation, by 2020, greenhouse gas emissions will decrease by 25 to 40 per cent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether the industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing or unwilling to provide material and technological assistance to those countries that need it.
A further agreement was reached on aid to developing countries.
The support fund provided for in the Kyoto Protocol will be directed by a steering board composed of 16 members, probably within the United Nations Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes "Piac es Profit".
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gabor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to preserve its avant-garde role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU undertakes to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020, regardless of whether or not the "after-2012 agreement" will be signed, and is willing to undertake to reduce even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to accept commitments in accordance with their responsibilities and capacities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol pledged to decrease by 5.2 per cent, within this period the 15 EU Member States committed to fulfilling 8 per cent of the decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce by 6 per cent the emissions of greenhouse gases from the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will meet - notes the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
It is a lot of what is at stake in Balí, since within two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force will be delayed by after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments, which are assumed in the Kyoto Protocol, would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, which was called for in its most recent report by the IPCC, the international scientific association of the United Nations dealing with climate change, which received the Nobel Peace Prize.
As a result, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2°C of the Earth's average temperature could not be prevented, according to scientists, from having irreversible and irreversible consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish recordings about actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
The British Air Force (RAD) first took advantage of YouTube services: the special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on helmets are controlled in the general body of Kandahar operations, then sent to London to be loaded on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are 139 recordings from air force soldiers who have been loaded in this way on the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions carried out in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the British Community (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had loaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the view of the Ministry of Defence, they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda costs virtually nothing compared to conventional recruiting television stations - told BBC the defence expert Gordon Mackenzie - in return, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to receptively edited and censored recordings, amateur videos appear in the distributor, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a few hypocrites, officials speak as much as possible of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fight.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have been uploaded from the battle fields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruiting with video shooting games, free downloadable, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers.
