At the same time as its parliamentary term, which ended today with the vote by the Congress of the amendments incorporated into the draft Senate, the Government has submitted to the public the regulation that will develop the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members and senators to negotiate and consensual the best regulation in order to ensure the protection of investors and to regulate in detail the activity of entities for the efficient functioning of markets.
The Mifid, which amends the Value Market Act, represents the modernisation of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and fostering cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new rules will enable financial advisory services to be provided to both specialised and legal firms and to create a new type of financial services signatures (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFI), which join value companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it expands the number of financial instrument operating systems so that regulated secondary markets are joined by multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also requires investment services undertakings to disclose information on the key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and risk management and requires them to keep a record of all their operations in order to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
In its move by the Congress Economic Commission, several amendments were incorporated, including stressing that debt securities are considered as a "complex" financial instrument given their high risk to the investor, which has been demonstrated by the US high-risk mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delimit the functions that diplomats can develop in Economics and Business 30 years after the real decree delimiting the professional functions reserved for economists was passed in 1977.
The Senate, for its part, incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as the mediator, who will work on an external basis, will not require the authorisation of the CNMV and may provide its product marketing and customer capture services to different investment firms at the same time.
